North to Alaska. Grandma Joy and Brad are out about in Alaska on their quest to visit all 63 National Parks. Make sure you are following to see all that @grandmajoysroadtrip is up to. We promise it’s all good. 
••••
Thanks to Grandma Joy and Brad @grandmajoysroadtrip for sharing the goodness of their adventures. 
•
Gates of the Arctic National Park and Preserve was US National Park #56 of 63 on Grandma Joy’s Road Trip! 

I spent years dreaming of the infinite possibilities we could achieve on this quest across our @nationalparkservice lands. Gates of the Arctic was one of those rare parks that seemed out of reach. “There is no way Grandma Joy will ever step foot on this land,” I thought. But time after time, my grandmother has defied the odds. I will look at this image for the rest of my life whenever I have the audacity to put limits on my dreams. You can do anything too.

Moments that make memories for a lifetime are National Park moments. 
•••••
Thanks to our friend Evan @wexplorations for sharing from his adventure. 
•
The grand finale to our time in @greatsmokynps: a glorious sunset, complete with the rolling fog of the mountains and, miraculously enough, a glowing red sun. I was spellbound by this. This was exactly the mental image of The Smokies that sustained me during these long and hard months of isolation and worry. To see it realized on the last night of our time here felt strangely inevitable; this wonderful moment I’d been thinking of for over a year was real and I was getting to see it. This fantastic sunset will be with me forever and I am so thankful I got to see it.

Happy 175th birthday to @smithsonian A visit to the National Mall would be incomplete without a stop at your favorite Smithsonian museum. We love @amhistorymuseum and @airandspacemuseum 
•••••
Thanks to @nationalmallnps for sharing the history. 
•
Happy 175th birthday to our neighbors on the National Mall: the Smithsonian Institution! Born an illegitimate child to a wealthy English father, James Smithson loved to study science. Making a name for himself as a scientist and innovator, Smithson traveled extensively for much of his life, but never once set foot on American soil. Despite that fact, when Smithson died in 1836, he willed his entire estate (valued at nearly $18 million today) to the United States of America to create “an establishment for the increase and diffusion of knowledge.” 

The motives behind Smithson’s bequest remain mysterious. Some have suggested that his gift was motivated in part by revenge against the rigidities of British society. Others have suggested it reflected his interest in the Enlightenment ideals of democracy and universal education. Whatever the reasons, on August 10, 1846, President James K. Polk signed the Smithsonian Act and formally established the prestigious organization that has become the world's largest museum, education, and research complex, with 19 museums, the National Zoo, and nine research facilities. For visitors to our nation's capital, experiencing the memorials on the National Mall and the museums and galleries of the Smithsonian Institution ( @Smithsonian ) are memories for a lifetime.

node.text:
Coastal sunsets are special in Acadia NP. 
••••
Thanks to John  @jkputnamphoto for the beautiful evening. 
•
Sunset two nights ago. Summer is an important time for me, it requires that I take a mental break from my own photography. This time of year I pretty much only go out with my camera when I’m with clients, which is often, and I end up standing in front of some pretty incredible scenes. Do I photograph them? Most certainly, and sometimes I get lucky with composition, but most of the time I’m making sure that those who put their trust in me, who invested time and money, are getting everything they want out of the experience. Giving that attention to others often means that my own work suffers. It doesn’t get the same attention from me as it would if I were out there alone. But what I get in return is more mental space allocated to enjoying the experience as well as the satisfaction of knowing that I provided an awesome experience for someone else. I learn more about what I do every season, and this season it has become clear that providing that experience should be my number one goal. I think I’ve always strived for that but I’ve just recently begun to understand how important it is. When we’re at location, camera set up, composition locked in, I try to remind people to watch the scene. Don’t look at it through your viewfinder, don’t watch it on your LCD… look over your camera, put yourself back into the scene, enjoy the experience, and when you see that magic moment happen, take the shot. As for me, well, I get to actually stand back and enjoy the sunset.

Night Sky Lovers, it’s time to look up and enjoy the annual Perseid Meteor shower. 
•••••
Thanks to Brandon  @bay.photography for the Joshua Tree goodness. 
•
The Perseid meteor shower peaks this week! This year, the moon will not obscure as it will only be at about 13% and will set well before the key times to look up. The best time will be mid-week around the 11th-13th close to midnight as the constellation Perseus rises up from the horizon. The origin of the meteors come from the Comet Swift-Tuttle which is in the direction of Perseus, towards the NE section of the sky. With any astro event, best piece of advice is to get out of the city away from light pollution to give yourself more opportunities to catch even the faintest meteors. Find an open area to lay back and enjoy the show.
